  <strong>Recursion vs iteration — practical explanation:</strong>
  <p class="small">
    Recursion means a function calls itself to solve a smaller instance of the same problem. For a fractal tree, the idea is: draw a branch, then recursively draw two smaller branches from its tip until a depth limit is reached. Recursion makes the code compact and expresses the problem naturally.
  </p>
  <p class="small">
    Stack overflow risk: every time a function calls another (including itself), the runtime pushes a stack frame storing arguments, return address, and local variables. Deep recursion can exhaust available stack memory, causing a stack overflow. JavaScript engines typically have recursion limits on the order of a few thousand nested calls — but limits vary and are much lower on some constrained environments.
  </p>

  <p class="small"><strong>Practical ways to avoid stack overflow:</strong></p>
  <ol class="small">
    <li>Use iterative algorithms (explicit stack or queue). Convert recursion to a loop that manages your own stack/queue data structure on the heap — heaps can grow larger than the call stack and are safer for deep traversals.</li>
    <li>Tail recursion (where supported). If the language/runtime optimizes tail calls (TCO) you can write tail-recursive code without growing the stack. JavaScript engines generally do not reliably provide TCO today, so this isn't portable.</li>
    <li>Increase the recursion base case. Limit recursion depth early; combine recursion with iteration for deeper levels (hybrid approach).</li>
    <li>Use techniques like continuation-passing or chunking: break work into small tasks and schedule with setTimeout/setImmediate/MessageChannel to yield and avoid deeply nested calls in one call stack.</li>
    <li>When building trees/graphs, do breadth-first traversal (queue) instead of depth-first recursion if stack depth is the worry.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small"><strong>Why the iterative approach below still demonstrates recursion:</strong> it uses an explicit stack where each stack entry represents a subtree that a recursive version would have processed with a call. The logic and state are identical to recursion, but you control the memory layout and avoid pushing frames onto the call stack.</p>

  <p class="small muted">Click "Show recursive code" to reveal a compact recursive function (for depth up to ~12 this is perfectly fine). The active drawing uses iterative method by default to avoid stack-overflow even for larger depths.</p>
